 Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bumpsteade","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Helion Bumpstead or Steeple Bumpstead (Essex)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bumstead","meanings":["English: habitational name from Bumpstead in Essex, early recorded as <i>Bumesteda</i>, from Old English <i>bune</i> ‘reed’ + <i>stede</i> ‘place, site’."]}]},{"name":"Grietes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Durham and Northumberland): variant of   Grieve  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: alternatively, a variant of   Greaves   or   Graves  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Grieve","meanings":["English:","occupational name for a steward or estate manager, from Middle English <i>greve</i> ‘steward, farm bailiff, or principal officer of a town’ (Old Northumbrian English <i>grǣfa</i>). Compare   Reeve   and   Sheriff  . The name is characteristic of northeastern England and southern and southeastern Scotland.","alternatively, a variant of   Grave  . These words were originally distinct, but some confusion has occurred as a result of the close similarity in both form and meaning."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":10,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":17